        <h3>Example: 5-person law firm</h3>
        <p>A personal injury firm runs WordPress (website), GA4 (analytics), Clio (legal CRM), and Mailchimp (email). Website generates organic traffic from 30 monthly blog posts. GA4 tracks consultation requests and attributes them to source. Mailchimp sends a monthly newsletter to past clients and referral sources. Four tools, cleanly integrated, covering the full client acquisition journey.</p>

        <h3>Example: Mid-size e-commerce brand</h3>
        <p>A D2C supplement brand with 35 employees uses Shopify (e-commerce), Klaviyo (email + SMS automation), GA4 (analytics), Meta Ads Manager (paid social), Semrush (SEO), Canva (design), and a social scheduling tool. Klaviyo syncs purchase data from Shopify to trigger post-purchase sequences, win-back campaigns, and VIP flows — all automated. Seven tools doing the work of a much larger team.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">MarTech Stack vs Sales Tech Stack — what's different?</h2>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>MarTech Stack</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Primary users: Marketing team</li>
              <li>Core tools: CMS, email, analytics, SEO, social</li>
              <li>Goal: Generate and nurture leads</li>
              <li>Key metrics: MQLs, traffic, engagement rate</li>
              <li>Overlap point: CRM, attribution</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Sales Tech Stack</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Primary users: Sales team</li>
              <li>Core tools: CRM, dialer, outreach sequencer, CPQ</li>
              <li>Goal: Close deals and manage pipeline</li>
              <li>Key metrics: Revenue, win rate, deal velocity</li>
              <li>Overlap point: CRM, analytics, attribution</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 MarTech Stack best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Define the problem before selecting the tool.</strong> "Better email" isn't a problem — "achieve 25% open rate for our nurture sequence" is. Specific requirements lead to specific tool selection. Vague requirements lead to buying whatever a vendor demos well.</li>
          <li><strong>Build around the CRM as central hub.</strong> Every other tool should be evaluated by how well it integrates with your CRM. A brilliant email tool that doesn't sync contact data back to the CRM creates a data silo that breaks attribution and reporting.</li>
          <li><strong>Audit annually, cut ruthlessly.</strong> Schedule a Q4 stack audit every year. List every tool, its cost, its primary user, and when it was last meaningfully used. Tools nobody can defend get cut. Redundant tools get consolidated. Teams consistently save 15–25% of martech spend this way.</li>
          <li><strong>Prioritize integration depth over feature completeness.</strong> A tool with 80% of the features you need that integrates cleanly with everything else beats a 100-feature tool that sits disconnected. Data flow between tools is worth more than features in any single tool.</li>
          <li><strong>Document every integration and automation.</strong> Write down what each tool does, who owns it, and how it connects to adjacent tools. When an integration breaks — and it will — documentation is what prevents a 2-hour investigation to figure out why leads stopped flowing to sales.</li>
          <li><strong>Train the team before adding new tools.</strong> The utilization gap (teams using 33% of stack capability on average) exists because tools get purchased before the team knows how to use them. Require a training plan as a condition of any new tool purchase.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common MarTech mistake — solving process problems with tool purchases</div>
          <p>A broken lead routing process doesn't need a new marketing automation tool — it needs the existing one configured correctly and a documented routing rule. A reporting gap doesn't need a new analytics platform — it needs UTM standards applied to existing campaigns. Before buying any new tool, ask: "Could we solve this problem by using what we already have better?" The answer is yes more often than vendors want you to know.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common MarTech Stack mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Building a stack without a CRM at the center</strong> — creates disconnected data silos where no tool has the full customer picture.</li>
          <li><strong>Tool sprawl from ad-hoc purchasing</strong> — each team member buying their own tools produces redundancy, fragmented data, and uncontrolled costs.</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping the integration layer</strong> — tools that don't share data require manual exports and imports, introducing errors and delays that undermine reporting accuracy.</li>
          <li><strong>No stack owner</strong> — without a designated MOps person or team, nobody is responsible for maintaining integrations, auditing usage, or training new team members.</li>
          <li><strong>Chasing enterprise tools at startup scale</strong> — Salesforce and Marketo are built for 500-person organizations. A 10-person team paying enterprise prices for features they can't use is burning budget on complexity.</li>
          <li><strong>Treating the stack as static</strong> — the MarTech landscape changes fast. A tool that was best-in-class 3 years ago may have been surpassed by a better-integrated or more cost-effective alternative.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
